  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD037093",
      "title": "Isolation and Characterization of ZK002, A Novel Dual Function Snake Venom Peptide from Deinagkistrodon acutus with Anti-angiogenic and Anti-inflammatory Properties",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Pathological angiogenesis, the abnormal or excessive generation of blood vessels, plays an important role in many diseases including cancer, diabetic retinopathy, psoriasis, and arthritis. Additionally, increasing evidence supports the close linkage between angiogenesis and inflammation. Snake venoms are a rich natural source of biologically active molecules and carry rich potential for the discovery anti-angiogenic and anti-inflammatory modulators. Here, we isolated and purified a novel protein, ZK002, from the venom of the snake Deinagkistrodon acutus, and investigated its anti-angiogenic and anti-inflammatory activities and mechanisms.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "Proteomics Sample Preparation The sample was added with its 4-fold volume -20oC pre-cooled acetone and incubated at -20oC for overnight to precipitate the protein. The sample was centrifuged at 12,000 x g for 15 mins and the supernatant was discarded. The protein pellet is resuspended with 8M urea, and the protein amount was quantified by a DC protein assay. 100\u00b5g protein sample was taken and top up the volume to 100 \u00b5L with 8M urea. Then the peptide reduction was with 25\u00b5L 200mM DTT solution and incubated at room temperature for 45 mins. After that, the peptide alkylation was with 4\u00b5L 1M IAA solution and incubated at room temperature for 20 mins in dark. Next, 671\u00b5L 50mM ammonium bicarbonate solution was added to dilute the urea concentration in the sample to 1 M. For trypsin digestion, 2\u00b5L of trypsin gold solution was added to the sample and incubated at 37oC overnight. 200\u00b5L MilliQ water and 7\u00b5L 100% TFA were added to the sample. Cleanup the digested peptide sample with QASIS HLB 1CC Extraction cartridges by washing with 0.5% TFA twice and eluting with 70% ACN twice. The eluate was dried with SpeedVac Vacuum Concentrator. Final, the sample was resuspended in 100\u00b5L 0.1% FA and transferred to an LC vial with an insert for Nano-LCMS analysis.  \u2003  Proteomics Mass Spectrometry The proteomics analysis was carried out on UltiMate\u2122 3000 RSLCnano System (Thermo Scientific) and Acclaim\u2122 PepMap\u2122 100 C18 Columns 250 mm (Thermo Scientific, Cat# 164569) with Orbitrap Fusion Lumos Mass Spectrometer(Thermo Scientific). The mobile included: 0.1 % formic acid in water as solvent A and 0.1 % formic acid in acetonitrile as solvent B. The NanoLC program was as follows: 0-10 mins B 2%; 10-12 mins B 2-6%; 12-47 mins B 6-20%; 47-52mins B 20-30%; 52-56mins B 30-90%; 56-61mins B 90%; 61-61.1mins B 90%-2%; 61.1-66mins B 2%.  The flow rate was 0.3 \u00b5L/mins, and the column temperature was 50oC. The detail of the MS condition was as follows: Mode of detection: positive mode; The scan range: 400-1500 m/z; Ionization Source: NSI; Spray Voltage: Static; Positive ion source voltage: 2300V; Ion transfer tube temperature: 300oC. The data acquisition was in parallel reaction monitoring (PRM) mode.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Proteomics Data Analysis  The ZK protein sequence was saved as a \u201c.fasta\u201d file and uploaded to Mascot Server(Matrix Science). The proteomics MS data was processed by Progenesis QI for Proteomics (Waters) with default setting. The peptide ion was identified by Mascot MS/MS ion search by following criteria. Peptide charge: 2+, 3+, 4+ ; Peptide tolerance: 10 Da(13C=2); MS/MS tolerance: 0.1 Da; Fixed modification: Carbamidomethyl(C); Variable modification: Oxidation(M); Enzyme: No specific; Max missed cleavages: 2; Instrument type: ESI-FTICR;",
      "projectTags": [],
      "keywords": [
        "Zk002; snake venom; anti-angiogenesis; anti-inflammation"
      ],
